1. Separated OrderBook by Symbol
Change
Created one OrderBook per symbol (BTC, ETH) inside SymbolEngine.
Why needed?
Each market must maintain its own independent liquidity and matching state.
Impact
✅ Multi-symbol support
✅ No cross-symbol contamination
✅ Easy horizontal scaling per symbol

2. Introduced Price-Level Order Book
Change
Used:TreeMap<Long, PriceLevel>
for: bids, asks
Each PriceLevel contains: price, FIFO deque of orders
Why needed?
To implement exchange-style price-time priority.
Impact
✅ Best bid/ask retrieval
✅ FIFO matching at same price
✅ Efficient price-level organization

3. Added cancelMap
Change
Introduced: HashMap<Long, OrderReference>
Why needed?
Avoid scanning the entire order book during cancellation.
Impact
✅ O(1) order lookup
✅ Faster cancel operations
✅ Realistic exchange design

4. Introduced Event-Driven Processing
Change
Created: EngineEvent, NewOrderEvent, CancelOrderEvent
and queued them in: BlockingQueue<EngineEvent>
Why needed?
To decouple order submission from matching.
Impact
✅ Asynchronous processing
✅ Better scalability
✅ Clean event-driven architecture

5. Implemented Single-Writer Model
Change
Each SymbolEngine runs its own matching thread.
Why needed?
Avoid locks and race conditions on shared order book state.
Impact
✅ Thread-safe matching
✅ No synchronization overhead
✅ Higher throughput

6. Extracted EngineManager
Change
Introduced central routing layer.
Why needed?
To route orders to correct symbol engine.
Impact
✅ Centralized symbol routing
✅ Easy symbol onboarding
✅ Cleaner orchestration

7. Added Order Validation Layer
Change
Validation before order enters book.
Examples: symbol, quantity, price, duplicate orderId
Why needed?
Prevent invalid state from entering engine.
Impact
✅ Data integrity
✅ Predictable behavior
✅ Cleaner API responses

8. Added Engine Response Events
Change
Introduced:
	ORDER_ACCEPTED
	ORDER_REJECTED
	TRADE_EXECUTED
	ORDER_PARTIALLY_FILLED
	ORDER_FILLED
	ORDER_CANCELLED
	CANCEL_REJECTED
Why needed?
Expose engine state changes externally.
Impact
✅ Real-time trade lifecycle
✅ Better observability
✅ Frontend integration ready

9. Introduced EngineResponsePublisher
Change
Abstracted event publishing through interface.
Why needed?
Separate matching logic from transport layer.
Impact
✅ Loose coupling
✅ Transport-independent engine
✅ Easier future extensions

10. Removed Publisher from Core Engine Constructor
Change
Publisher moved from engine construction to per-event context.
Why needed?
Socket connections are short-lived; engine instances are long-lived.
Impact
✅ Correct dependency lifecycle
✅ Multi-client support
✅ Cleaner architecture

11. Added TCP Transport Layer
Change
Created: EngineSocketServer, ClientHandler, SocketResponsePublisher
Why needed?
Connect Node.js gateway with Java engine.
Impact
✅ Persistent low-latency communication
✅ Real-time bidirectional messaging
✅ Exchange-style gateway architecture

12. Extracted Transport from Main Application
Change
Removed socket parsing from MatchingEngineApp.
Why needed?
Main should only bootstrap services.
Impact
✅ Cleaner separation of concerns
✅ Better maintainability
✅ Production-style startup flow

13. Switched to Request/Response Event Flow
Change
Each inbound event carries: business data, response publisher
Why needed?
Allow engine to respond to the correct client connection.
Impact
✅ Multi-client compatibility
✅ Correct request-response mapping
✅ Transport-aware event processing

Current Architecture
	Node REST API      
	↓TCP Socket      
	↓ClientHandler      
	↓EngineManager      
	↓SymbolEngine (single writer)      
	↓OrderBook      
	↓EngineResponsePublisher      
	↓Node/WebSocket/UI
Overall Impact
✅ Exchange-style architecture
✅ Event-driven
✅ Thread-safe
✅ Multi-symbol
✅ Real-time publish/subscribe ready
✅ Resume-worthy systems project